# CROSS-LANGUAGE CLI LIBRARY TAXONOMY — AXIS 42 CONTINUES:
#   MARKDOWN PARSING / COMMONMARK CODECS (Go side)
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# This completion **CONTINUES AXIS 42** in the cross-
# language CLI library taxonomy.  R757 Rust=97 (basalt/
# pulldown-cmark OPENS Axis 42) → R758 Go=97 (tdx/
# yuin/goldmark CONTINUES Axis 42 THIS ROUND).
# Pending: R759 TS-Node=97 with a marked or markdown-it
# user to close Axis 42 at 1/1/1.
#
# WHY yuin/goldmark IS A DISTINCTIVE AXIS-42
# CONTINUATION:
#
#   github.com/yuin/goldmark by Yusuke Inuzuka is the
#   de-facto Go CommonMark + GFM parser, displacing
#   the older blackfriday + bluemonday stack as the
#   standard choice in modern Go projects since circa
#   2020.  Distinguishing characteristics:
#     1. COMMONMARK 0.31 SPEC COMPLIANCE — passes the
#        full CommonMark 0.31 specification test
#        suite (the normative test corpus); strict
#        adherence to spec edge cases
#     2. GFM EXTENSIONS via extension packages —
#        opt-in via `goldmark.New(goldmark.WithExtensions(
#          extension.GFM,           // tables, strikethrough,
#                                    // linkify, tasklist
#          extension.Footnote,
#          extension.DefinitionList,
#          extension.Linkify,
#          extension.Table,
#          extension.Strikethrough,
#          extension.TaskList,      // - [ ] / - [x]
#          extension.Typographer,
#          ...
#        ))`.  Users pay only for the extensions they
#        enable; tdx uses TaskList specifically for
#        its checkbox parsing
#     3. AST-BASED — exposes Markdown as a traversable
#        AST (`ast.Node` interface tree) rather than
#        an event stream.  Tradeoff: slightly heavier
#        than streaming, but enables easier
#        transformations like tdx's "find every task-
#        list-item, toggle its CheckboxState"
#     4. RENDERER PIPELINE — renderers register node
#        handlers via `r.Register(KindFoo, fooHandler)`;
#        custom output formats (HTML, terminal text,
#        re-emitted Markdown) plug in via the same
#        interface
#     5. EXTENSION ECOSYSTEM — `goldmark-emoji`
#        (emoji shortcodes), `goldmark-highlighting`
#        (syntax-highlighted code blocks via
#        chroma), `goldmark-meta` (YAML frontmatter
#        parsing), `goldmark-mathjax` (math), `goldmark-
#        wikilink` (Obsidian-style links), etc.
#     6. ZERO-COPY where possible — `text.Reader`
#        provides slice-based access to the source
#        buffer; many parser operations avoid
#        allocations
#     7. ~3,700+ STARS ON yuin/goldmark
#     8. ECOSYSTEM-DOMINANT — used by Hugo (the
#        dominant Go static site generator), gh-eco,
#        mdblog, crd-wizard, gopher-code, raystack/
#        stencil, gohugoio's many extensions, tdx
#        (this completion), and effectively every
#        modern Go project that processes Markdown
#
# Maintained under github.com/yuin/goldmark.  License:
# MIT.
#
